<validation>
1. Cross-reference multiple indicators - don't rely on single header.
2. Confirm version numbers through multiple sources.
3. Test framework-specific paths to validate detection.
4. Trigger errors intentionally to see real stack traces.
5. Check if CDN is masking the origin server technology.
6. Verify JavaScript library versions at runtime if possible.
7. Map confirmed technologies to CVE databases.
</validation>

<false_positives>
- CDN headers masking origin server (Cloudflare showing nginx when origin is Apache)
- Custom Server headers hiding real technology
- Generic error pages not revealing actual framework
- Deprecated headers left from migrations
- Load balancer headers not representing application stack
- JavaScript bundlers obscuring library versions
- Docker/container layers adding extra headers
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Accurate fingerprinting enables targeted exploit selection
- Version detection reveals applicable CVEs and vulnerabilities
- Framework identification guides testing methodology
- CMS detection enables plugin/theme vulnerability scanning
- Database detection informs injection payload crafting
- API technology identification shapes API testing approach
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always check multiple endpoints - /api, /admin, /login may reveal different technologies.
2. Force errors with malformed input to expose stack traces.
3. Check /robots.txt and /sitemap.xml for technology hints.
4. Look at HTTP/2 behavior - some servers have distinct implementations.
5. Analyze 404 pages - custom vs default reveals framework.
6. Check response timing patterns under load.
7. Use Wappalyzer signatures as reference but verify manually.
8. Don't trust Server headers alone - they're easily spoofed.
9. Check JavaScript source maps for unminified library versions.
10. Monitor for technology changes during testing - deployments happen.
</pro_tips>

<remember>Technology fingerprinting is not a single check but a continuous process of evidence gathering. High-confidence identification requires multiple corroborating indicators. Always map findings to actionable attack vectors and known vulnerabilities.</remember>
</tech_fingerprinter_guide>
